{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17536555","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17536555"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:08:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15802"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15802","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15802"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.12,0.45,0.2,0.2,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8493"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113480"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8493","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8493"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15802"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95497"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1540"},{"type":"tags","id":"2756"},{"type":"tags","id":"3789"},{"type":"tags","id":"4025"},{"type":"tags","id":"4440"},{"type":"tags","id":"4459"},{"type":"tags","id":"12800"},{"type":"tags","id":"12805"},{"type":"tags","id":"12909"},{"type":"tags","id":"12917"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20406"},{"type":"contributions","id":"39765"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45866"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46683"},{"type":"contributions","id":"46744"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48130"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"113480","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/113480"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman is reviewed on the Labour Ward with ongoing heavy vaginal bleeding after delivering her first baby vaginally 30 minutes ago following a prolonged second stage of labour. She has received active management of the third stage with oxytocin. She has lost an estimated 2000 mL of blood. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears pale and diaphoretic. Her pulse rate is 125/min, blood pressure 85/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 36.2\u00b0C. Her uterus feels boggy on palpation. Investigations reveal: haemoglobin 72 g/L (115-160), platelet count 85 x 10^9/L (150-400), activated partial thromboplastin time 45 seconds (25-35), international normalised ratio 1.8 (0.9-1.2).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most important next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tranexamic acid","Packed red blood cells","Ergometrine","Crystalloid fluid","Misoprostol"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe primary postpartum haemorrhage (PPH) with clinical signs of shock and significant blood loss. The laboratory results show anaemia, thrombocytopenia and coagulopathy, indicating the need for urgent blood product replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough in the case of a PPH many actions are often carried out in tandem, the organisation and administration of \u003Cstrong\u003Epacked red blood cells\u003C/strong\u003E are the most important next step given the severe anaemia (haemoglobin 72 g/L) and ongoing bleeding with haemodynamic compromise. The priority is to restore oxygen-carrying capacity and maintain tissue perfusion. This would likely be part of a massive transfusion or Rotem guided transfusion protocol for this patient. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETranexamic acid\u003C/strong\u003E should be given early in PPH to reduce mortality, but in this scenario with severe anaemia and shock, blood product replacement takes precedence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EErgometrine\u003C/strong\u003E is a second-line uterotonic agent that can be used for uterine atony, but would not address the immediate need for volume and red cell replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrystalloid fluid\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inadequate given the severity of blood loss and anaemia. While crystalloids may be given alongside blood products, they do not address the oxygen-carrying capacity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMisoprostol\u003C/strong\u003E is another uterotonic agent that can be used for uterine atony, but like ergometrine, it would not address the immediate need for blood product replacement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of massive PPH requires a multi-modal approach including mechanical measures (uterine massage, balloon tamponade), pharmacological therapy (uterotonics, tranexamic acid), and appropriate blood product replacement. A massive transfusion protocol should be activated early, with consideration of point-of-care testing such as ROTEM/TEG to guide blood product replacement.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Primary postpartum haemorrhage with coagulopathy requires early blood product replacement including fibrinogen.","ROTEM/TEG guided blood product replacement can be helpful to guide product replacement for massive PPH"],"references":["Queensland Health. Primary Postpartum Haemorrhage (PPH) Prevention and Management Guideline [Internet]. Brisbane: Queensland Health; 2022 [cited 2024 Nov 18]. Available from: https://www.health.qld.gov.au/__data/assets/pdf_file/0015/140136/g-pph.PDF"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"95497"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15802"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRe